  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD066867",
      "title": "3x-HA Tagged PAF1 IP-Ms in MOLM-13 CAS9 cells",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "Transcriptional regulatory proteins are frequent drivers of oncogenesis and common targets for drug discovery. The transcriptional co-activator, ENL, which binds to chromatin through an acetyllysine reader YEATS domain, is preferentially required for the survival and pathogenesis of acute leukemia. Small molecules that inhibit the ENL YEATS domain show anti-leukemia effects in preclinical models, which is thought to be caused by the downregulation of pro-leukemic ENL target genes. However, the transcriptional effects of ENL YEATS domain inhibitors have not been studied in models of intrinsic or acquired resistance and, therefore, the connection between proximal transcriptional effects and downstream anti-proliferative effects is poorly understood. To address this, we identified models of intrinsic and acquired resistance and used them to study the effects of ENL YEATS domain inhibitors. We first discovered that ENL YEATS domain inhibition produces similar transcriptional responses in naive models of sensitive and resistant leukemia. We then performed a CRISPR/Cas9-based genetic modifier screen and identified in-frame deletions of the essential transcriptional regulator, PAF1, that confer resistance to ENL YEATS domain inhibitors. Using isogenic models of PAF1-mediated resistance, we again found that the downregulation of ENL target genes is shared in both sensitive and resistant leukemia. Altogether, these data support the conclusion that the suppression of ENL target genes is not sufficient to explain the anti-leukemia effects of ENL antagonists.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "MOLM-13 Cells stably expressing 3x-HA tagged PAF1 constructs were collected (following 4hr 10 \u00b5M SR-0813 treatment in the treated conditions) and washed twice with ice cold PBS. Cell pellets were lysed in 1ml of IP-Lysis buffer (50mM EPPS pH 7.5, 150mM NaCl, 1% NP-40, 10% glycerol, 1mM MgCl2 , 1:1000 benzonase nuclease, and EDTA-free protease inhibitor tablet) at 4 deg for 2 hours while rotating. Lysate was collected following 12,000xg spin 5min at 4deg to remove insoluble debris and the concentration was determined via a BCA assay. 2.5mg of lysate was added to 40ul of prewashed anti-HA magnetic beads ( Cat# 88836) for 2-4 hours incubation at 4\u00baC with rotation. The samples were placed on a magnetic rack and washed three times with IP wash buffer (25mM EPPS, pH 7.5, 150mM NaCl, 0.2% NP-40) and once briefly with EPPS pH 8.0. Enriched proteins were eluted from the beads by boiling with 40 \u00b5l of fresh 8 M urea in 50mM EPPS pH 8.0, at 65\u00baC for 10 mins.  Each sample was then reduced with 2 \u00b5l of 200mM DTT and incubated at 65\u00baC for 15 min and alkylated with 2 \u00b5l of 400mM iodoacetamide incubated at 37\u00baC for 30 minutes in the shaker. Samples were further diluted to 2M urea with115ul of 50mM EPPS bringing each sample volume to 160ul. Trypsin was reconstituted using 60ul of 50mM EPPS pH 8.0 and  20ul of 100mM CaCl2. 4ul of reconstituted trypsin was added to each sample and they were incubated at 37\u00baC overnight (no more that 16 hours) while shaking.  The following day 35ul of acetonitrile was added per sample and the samples were water bath sonicated for 5minutes. Samples were TMT tagged with 5 \u00b5l of each TMT tag, vortexed, and left at room temperature for 1hr before the addition of 5 \u00b5l of 5% hydroxylamine was added to each sample and incubated for 15 minutes at room temperature. After incubation 5 \u00b5l of 100% formic acid was added to each sample all labeled samples were combined into a 2ml tube and placed on the SpeedVac overnight. Samples were desalted using a Sep-Pak column and then high pH fractionated into three fractions using peptide desalting columns.Pooled samples were desalted by resuspending with 500ul Velos Buffer A (95% H20, 5% ACN, 0.1% Formic acid) with the addition of 20 \u00b5l formic acid and then water bath sonicated for 5 minutes. The Sep-Pak C18 Cartridge was conditioned with the addition of 1ml 100% ACN (3x) and equilibrated with 1mL Velos Buffer A. The sample was loaded to the column and allowed to drip slowly, the flowthrough was re-added to the column for a second time. Bound sample was desalted with 3 washes of Velos buffer A (1 ml), and then eluted with 1ml of 80% ACN/ 0.1% formic acid. The sample was then dried using the SpeedVac. High-pH fractionation was carried out following the previously reported methods using peptide desalting spin columns (Thermo 89852). Samples were resuspended in 300 \u00b5L velos buffer A by water bath sonication. The peptide desalting column was prepared by washing with 300 \u00b5l acetonitrile (2x) and with 300 ul of 0.1% formic acid in water (2x). Resuspended peptides were then loaded onto the column and the flowthrough was readded to the column for a second time. Bound peptides were then washed once with 300 \u00b5l of H2O and once with 300 \u00b5l of5% acetonitrile in 10mM NH4HCO3 and eluted into 9 fractions with increasing gradient of acetonitrile. Every third fraction was combined and dried with the SpeedVac. Dried TMT-labelled peptide digest fractions were solubilized in 20 \u03bcL 1% TFA and desalted using 2\u03bcg capacity ZipTips (Millipore, Billerica, MA), according to manufacturer instructions. They were then dried under vacuum.",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "Raw data files were processed as described in Njomen et al. Uploaded to the Integrated Proteomics Pipeline (IP2, version 6.0.2) available here http://ip2.scripps.edu/ip2/mainMenu.html, and MS2 and MS3 files were then extracted with RAW Converter (http://fields.scripps.edu/rawconv/) and searched using the ProLuCID algorithm to the Human UniProt database.",
